{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6e912cf3-a784-4e4c-a7aa-e0e8583291f6","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\nAfter an SDK update, your installed workloads (like `maui`) may be pinned to versions that are incompatible with the new SDK. `dotnet workload update` downloads the **latest compatible versions** of all installed workloads, which is exactly what you need.\n\n`dotnet workload repair` only **reinstalls the same versions** already recorded — it fixes corrupted installations but won't resolve a version mismatch caused by an SDK update.\n\n**TL;DR:**\n\n| Command | What it does | When to use |\n|---|---|---|\n| `workload update` | Installs latest compatible versions | After SDK updates ✅ |\n| `workload repair` | Reinstalls current versions | Corrupted/broken installs |\n\nIf the build still fails afterward, run `dotnet workload list` to confirm the `maui` workload is installed and up to date.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b013266f-f984-4141-bb8a-fb54e2bc355b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after an SDK update broke their build.\n\nThis is a general knowledge question, not a codebase task. I can answer directly.\n\n- `dotnet workload update` — downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads. Use this after an SDK update to bring workloads in sync with the new SDK.\n- `dotnet workload repair` — reinstalls all installed workloads to fix a corrupted installation, but does NOT update them to newer versions.\n\nSince the user updated the SDK, the workloads are likely mismatched (old workload versions vs new SDK). `dotnet workload update` is the right choice.","outputTokens":404,"requestId":"483A:6A01C:76C53CE:83054E3:69F3FA04"},"id":"93ce39b8-796c-4d31-b35f-26e5587f2ce6","timestamp":"2026-05-01T00:55:41.908Z","parentId":"5c6536a7-70dc-4185-921b-e20828af43df"}
